{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_0187anNynqtfjKXfLswNdQQ3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The issue is that the `import.sql` runs before JPA schema creation. The `import.sql` tries to insert into `ApplicationSettings` table but it doesn't exist yet. With `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create-drop`, Hibernate creates the schema. The problem is the ordering: `spring.sql.init.data-locations` runs before JPA. \n\nThe fix is to either:\n1. Remove the `spring.sql.init` configuration and let `SampleDataGenerator` handle everything, or\n2. Use `spring.jpa.defer-datasource-initialization=true` (which we already have - let me check the actual error more carefully)\n\nActually, looking at the error and our `application.properties`, we have `spring.jpa.defer-datasource-initialization=true`. But the `import.sql` has an insert for `ApplicationSettings` table which is a JPA entity. Let me check if this entity exists:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2999,"cache_read_input_tokens":122691,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2999,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":362},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8543075e-efdd-4cb8-9429-6656037679ab","uuid":"6fb5a958-9790-425d-8c13-cc439a2d1883"}
