{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0134r6tuFu6Nrn6XWBfja3nJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.application.util;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import jakarta.persistence.Entity;\n     5→import jakarta.persistence.Id;\n     6→\n     7→/**\n     8→ * Application settings. Although this is stored in the database, it is not a true part of the\n     9→ * domain model but simply an application infrastructure artifact.\n    10→ */\n    11→@Entity\n    12→public class ApplicationSettings implements Serializable {\n    13→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    14→\n    15→  @Id\n    16→  private Long id;\n    17→\n    18→  private boolean sampleLoaded = false;\n    19→\n    20→  public boolean isSampleLoaded() {\n    21→    return sampleLoaded;\n    22→  }\n    23→\n    24→  public void setSampleLoaded(boolean sampleLoaded) {\n    25→    this.sampleLoaded = sampleLoaded;\n    26→  }\n    27→}\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8543075e-efdd-4cb8-9429-6656037679ab","uuid":"5a8b3935-c8ef-41b8-bc4a-b9ee7d9bd6ed"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_011iTFMBQdNpjhT1KQSuXtnu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The entity exists, and we have `spring.jpa.defer-datasource-initialization=true` which should make SQL init run after JPA. The problem might be the H2 column case sensitivity or the path issue with file-based H2 in Docker. Let me also check the full container logs for the actual root error more carefully. The real issue is likely that the SQL init ran before JPA DDL. Let me check if the setting is actually being picked up, or if there's a spring.batch issue creating a conflict.\n\nThe issue is that Spring Batch also initializes its schema tables (`spring.batch.jdbc.initialize-schema=always`) and this might interfere. Let me fix the configuration:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":491,"cache_read_input_tokens":126429,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":491,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":264},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8543075e-efdd-4cb8-9429-6656037679ab","uuid":"5277e458-357f-4bfc-af96-2faf9a8bd1ef"}
